+# Chain 01 - Family-Level Template-Defect Theorem On `F_SL(rho)`
+
+## Central Premise
+
+Step `006` already froze the first exact theorem question for repaired
+`Template-Defect Near-Closure`:
+compute the exact
+`rho`-dependence of
+`G_tmpl(P_n; I) = (Delta_tmpl, Delta_spec)`
+on the carried scale-separated family
+`F_SL(rho)` for `0 < rho <= 1/16`.
+
+The cleanest next result is therefore not another audit. It is one
+family-level admissibility theorem, or a sharp family-level failure memo, on
+the same frozen packet sheet and window.
+
+## Verifiable Result Target
+
+Either:
+
+- a proposition-scale statement that the frozen family
+  `F_SL(rho)`
+  satisfies the repaired template sheet
+  `Delta_tmpl <= 1/4`,
+  `Delta_spec <= 49/256`
+  uniformly for
+  `0 < rho <= 1/16`,
+  with the extremal case identified exactly; or
+- a bounded negative result showing that the recorded friendly boundary witness
+  `F_SL(1/16)` is not truly extremal, the repaired sheet is not exact on this
+  family, or the observable cannot be closed without hidden bookkeeping.
+
+## Why This Chain Is Meaningfully Different
+
+This chain is purely about the role-template observable on one carried family.
+It does not try to prove a leakage theorem, search a whole admissible region,
+or construct a counterexample dynamically.
+
+## Ordered Steps
+
+### Step 1 - Freeze The Exact `F_SL(rho)` Theorem Sheet
+
+Depends on: none.
+
+Action: freeze the exact theorem object from the Step-6 handoff:
+the canonical one-bridge packet sheet,
+role order,
+fixed window `I = [0, 1]`,
+repaired defect thresholds
+`(1/4, 49/256)`,
+the fixed shell ratio
+`|k_{n+1}| / |k_n| = 8`,
+and the frozen sign/phase sheets
+`sigma_SL`,
+`phi_SL`.
+
+Action: write the exact parameter list for
+`F_SL(rho)`,
+including which packet coordinates depend on
+`rho`
+and which are frozen by canonicalization.
+
+Expected output: one theorem setup sheet that names the carried family,
+its admissible parameter interval,
+and the exact observable to be proved or disproved.
+
+Kill condition: if the carried family cannot be written as one exact
+canonicalized parameter family on the current ledger, stop and report that the
+Step-6 theorem question was underspecified.
+
+### Step 2 - Derive The Exact Template-Defect Ledger On The Family
+
+Depends on: Step 1.
+
+Action: derive the exact role-projected quantities entering the retained
+diagnostic vector
+`v_tmpl(F_SL)`,
+including the desired-channel coordinates and spectator-defect coordinates that
+feed
+`Delta_tmpl(rho)`
+and
+`Delta_spec(rho)`.
+
+Action: keep the computation in the frozen interaction currency. Do not import
+new thresholds, regroup the packet, or renormalize away the carried
+spectators.
+
+Expected output: a closed-form ledger or rigorously checked symbolic table for
+`Delta_tmpl(rho)` and `Delta_spec(rho)` on the full carried interval.
+
+Kill condition: if the exact defect coordinates only close after hidden
+retuning of the packet semantics, the chain fails as a theorem route.
+
+### Step 3 - Prove Or Refute The Recorded Boundary Witness
+
+Depends on: Step 2.
+
+Action: determine whether the worst friendly case really occurs at
+`rho = 1/16`,
+as the Step-6 handoff currently suggests, or whether a different extremal
+parameter occurs on the same carried family.
+
+Action: prove the needed monotonicity, convexity, or explicit maximization
+statement in the carried interval. If the current boundary witness is wrong,
+replace it only with another parameter value from the same frozen family.
+
+Expected output: an extremal-parameter lemma and a corrected family boundary
+sheet if correction is necessary.
+
+Kill condition: if the defect observable oscillates or changes truth value in
+an uncontrolled way across the carried interval, the current family theorem
+object is too unstable to promote.
+
+### Step 4 - Decide Whether Same-Currency Hostile Separation Is Earned
+
+Depends on: Step 3.
+
+Action: attempt one same-currency hostile comparison using an explicit frozen
+subfamily of
+`F_DT(delta, eta)`.
+Only use a hostile comparison if the needed wavevector/helicity ledger can be
+written on disk without inventing new data.
+
+Action: if that hostile ledger can be pinned honestly, compute the resulting
+template-defect separation on the same observable. If it cannot, keep the
+theorem family-local and record the hostile comparison as an unresolved debt
+rather than smuggling it in.
+
+Expected output: either a same-currency hostile comparison sheet or a narrow
+note explaining why the theorem remains family-local at this stage.
+
+Kill condition: if hostile separation requires made-up
+`F_DT`
+numerics or a new packet model, drop the hostile clause instead of weakening
+the honesty standard.
+
+### Step 5 - Package The Strongest Honest Endpoint
+
+Depends on: Step 4.
+
+Action: package one of two exact outcomes:
+either a family-level admissibility theorem for
+`F_SL(rho)`
+under
+`G_tmpl`,
+or a bounded negative memo saying exactly why the repaired template sheet does
+not survive family-level exact closure.
+
+Action: state explicitly whether the result is only a family theorem or whether
+the branch earned an additional hostile separation clause.
+
+Expected output: a proposition candidate or a narrow negative memo with the
+failure bucket named precisely.
+
+Kill condition: if the final statement needs leakage implications,
+behavior-itinerary claims, or broader packet classes that were not proved in
+the chain, cut it back until it is fully family-local.
